column7: Income from Total Income (Annual income (Lempira)) Urban sample
column8: page: 153; table: 7; table label: Table 7. ITT estimation results (2) income outcomes; row label: Panel A: Urban sample, Coef.; column label: (1) Total Income
column9: coef, p asterisks, std error in same col
column11:
I did not map outcome effect "outcome balance" table 5 as authors consider this different from total saving see footnote 19. 
Authors do not specify which of the urban or rural sample represent the "preferred" specification. Authors discuss both results from the urban and rural samples. Observations are averaged at the village level in the rural sample (individual level for the urban sample). This is due to the random assignment of the intervention, see below:
"In urban areas, CCT beneficiaries were stratified at the municipality level and individuals were randomly assigned to either the treatment or control groups. In rural areas, the unit of randomisation was at the village level. In total, there were 27 village clusters. " p147
"measured at the individual level in urban areas and averaged at the village level in rural areas" p148

column5: Assessing the Impacts and Spillover Effects of Multifaceted Graduation Programs in a Pastoralist Region
column8: page: 79; table: 4.2; table label: Table 4.2. Average Treatment Effects Midline and Endline; row label: Women’s Business Assets ($PPP); column label: Treatment Waves 1-2, Midline
column9: coef, p asterisks, std error in same col
column11:
Waves 1-2 Midline: effect after 18-24 months in the programme
Time of effect is quite complicated: 
“Data was collected in three rounds: baseline in 2018, midline in 2020 (pre-COVID), and endline in 2022" p3
"By the time of midline data collection, BOMA women started the programs in different waves had been enrolled for different durations. (i.e. wave 1 women would have been in the program for 24 months, wave 2 for 18 months, wave 3 for 12 months and wave 4 for 6 months)." p222
 “At midline, wave 1 women had just graduated from the program, wave 2 women were 18 months into the program, wave 3 women were 12 months in, and wave 4 women had been in the program for 6 months. Wave 5 women, on the other hand, entered the program after the midline and had been in the program for 18-24 months by the time of the endline data collection.” P77
“Wave 5 women, on the other hand, entered the program after the midline and had been in the program for 18-24 months by the time of the endline data collection. “ p78
“With the endline data collected at the beginning of 2022” p68
Relevant estimates are in chapter 4: "The second chapter delves into the spillover effects of the REAP program through the female kinship network within local communities." pii
"In Chapter 2, we demonstrate that, once the spillover effects onto the non-treated women are taken into account, the REAP program has significant positive impacts on women’s productive assets, family cash income, and financial savings." p67
"With the endline data collected at the beginning of 2022, we aim to examine the medium to long-term effects of the graduation program in the pastoralist regions." p67
